-- ========== 1: The Psychology of Nostalgia (過去問風) ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'The Psychology of Nostalgia\n\nIn the late seventeenth century, a physician observed that soldiers far from home often suffered from a condition we would now associate with intense longing for their native land. He attributed this to psychological rather than purely physical causes. Not everyone at the time accepted that __BLANK__. Some argued instead that climate or diet was to blame, and others proposed that certain sounds or sights triggered the affliction.\n\nBy the early nineteenth century, the term "nostalgia" had come to denote a form of melancholy or depression. Later, scholars such as Fred Davis argued that nostalgia in modern usage carries positive associations—fond memories of the past, childhood, or "the good old days"—unlike the suffering of those uprooted soldiers. __BLANK__ is now widely accepted: nostalgia as a bittersweet emotion is distinct from simple homesickness as a debilitating condition.\n\nRecent research suggests that nostalgia __BLANK__. Studies indicate that although nostalgic feelings are sometimes triggered by sadness or loss, they often involve reframing difficult experiences in a positive light. Strong nostalgic experiences have been correlated with greater happiness, higher self-esteem, and a reduced fear of mortality. Psychologists increasingly view nostalgia as a psychological resource rather than a weakness.',
  'The Psychology of Nostalgia',
  E'The Psychology of Nostalgia\n\nIn the late seventeenth century, a physician observed that soldiers far from home often suffered from a condition we would now associate with intense longing for their native land. He attributed this to psychological rather than purely physical causes. Not everyone at the time accepted that __BLANK__. Some argued instead that climate or diet was to blame, and others proposed that certain sounds or sights triggered the affliction.\n\nBy the early nineteenth century, the term "nostalgia" had come to denote a form of melancholy or depression. Later, scholars such as Fred Davis argued that nostalgia in modern usage carries positive associations—fond memories of the past, childhood, or "the good old days"—unlike the suffering of those uprooted soldiers. __BLANK__ is now widely accepted: nostalgia as a bittersweet emotion is distinct from simple homesickness as a debilitating condition.\n\nRecent research suggests that nostalgia __BLANK__. Studies indicate that although nostalgic feelings are sometimes triggered by sadness or loss, they often involve reframing difficult experiences in a positive light. Strong nostalgic experiences have been correlated with greater happiness, higher self-esteem, and a reduced fear of mortality. Psychologists increasingly view nostalgia as a psychological resource rather than a weakness.'
);
