-- ========== 2: Invasive Species and Ecosystems (過去問風) ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'Invasive Species and Ecosystems\n\nCertain ant species have become formidable invaders when introduced to new continents. In their native range, periodic flooding forces them to abandon their nests and compete fiercely with other ants for territory. __BLANK__ shaped their evolution: over time they became highly aggressive and territorial, traits that served them well when they were later transported by human activity to regions where they had no natural competitors.\n\nThese ants rarely breed with other species and often eliminate rival colonies. Their genetic uniformity is an advantage in one respect: they recognize members of their own group easily and avoid wasteful conflict among themselves. This allows them to __BLANK__, forming vast supercolonies that overwhelm native ant populations. To casual observers they may seem harmless—small and without a painful sting—but their numbers and coordination make them devastating to local fauna.\n\nTheir impact extends beyond direct competition. __BLANK__: in some regions, predators that once fed on the larger native ants now refuse to eat the invaders, leading to declines in those predator populations. In other areas, the invaders have displaced native ants that played a crucial role in dispersing seeds, without fulfilling that ecological function themselves. The full consequences of such invasions are still being studied.',
  'Invasive Species and Ecosystems',
  E'Invasive Species and Ecosystems\n\nCertain ant species have become formidable invaders when introduced to new continents. In their native range, periodic flooding forces them to abandon their nests and compete fiercely with other ants for territory. __BLANK__ shaped their evolution: over time they became highly aggressive and territorial, traits that served them well when they were later transported by human activity to regions where they had no natural competitors.\n\nThese ants rarely breed with other species and often eliminate rival colonies. Their genetic uniformity is an advantage in one respect: they recognize members of their own group easily and avoid wasteful conflict among themselves. This allows them to __BLANK__, forming vast supercolonies that overwhelm native ant populations. To casual observers they may seem harmless—small and without a painful sting—but their numbers and coordination make them devastating to local fauna.\n\nTheir impact extends beyond direct competition. __BLANK__: in some regions, predators that once fed on the larger native ants now refuse to eat the invaders, leading to declines in those predator populations. In other areas, the invaders have displaced native ants that played a crucial role in dispersing seeds, without fulfilling that ecological function themselves. The full consequences of such invasions are still being studied.'
);
