-- ========== 5: The Brain as Predictor (過去問風) ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'The Brain as Predictor\n\nTraditional views of perception assumed that the brain passively receives sensory input and then processes it. According to a growing body of research, however, the brain can more accurately be described as __BLANK__. It constantly generates expectations based on past experience, current context, and learned associations. For example, you may feel your thirst quenched soon after drinking, even though the water has not yet been fully absorbed—your brain is predicting the outcome.\n\nNeurons fire in dynamic patterns that spread across regions. When you see something ambiguous—a shape that could be a branch or a snake—your brain settles on one interpretation, and that interpretation becomes your conscious experience. Remarkably, this can happen __BLANK__. If your brain concludes that the object is a snake, it may prepare your body to react before the visual cortex has finished processing the image. Anticipation and reaction can precede full perceptual confirmation.\n\nThe way the brain operates __BLANK__. Consider anxiety before public speaking: the brain may raise your heart rate and make your hands perspire before you have said a word. Yet the same predictive machinery can be trained. By reframing how we interpret bodily signals and situations, we can turn anxiety into focused energy. Research on such techniques suggests that understanding the brain''s predictive nature can help people build resilience and adapt more effectively to stress.',
  'The Brain as Predictor',
  E'The Brain as Predictor\n\nTraditional views of perception assumed that the brain passively receives sensory input and then processes it. According to a growing body of research, however, the brain can more accurately be described as __BLANK__. It constantly generates expectations based on past experience, current context, and learned associations. For example, you may feel your thirst quenched soon after drinking, even though the water has not yet been fully absorbed—your brain is predicting the outcome.\n\nNeurons fire in dynamic patterns that spread across regions. When you see something ambiguous—a shape that could be a branch or a snake—your brain settles on one interpretation, and that interpretation becomes your conscious experience. Remarkably, this can happen __BLANK__. If your brain concludes that the object is a snake, it may prepare your body to react before the visual cortex has finished processing the image. Anticipation and reaction can precede full perceptual confirmation.\n\nThe way the brain operates __BLANK__. Consider anxiety before public speaking: the brain may raise your heart rate and make your hands perspire before you have said a word. Yet the same predictive machinery can be trained. By reframing how we interpret bodily signals and situations, we can turn anxiety into focused energy. Research on such techniques suggests that understanding the brain''s predictive nature can help people build resilience and adapt more effectively to stress.'
);
