-- ========== 6: Evolutionary Anachronisms (過去問風) ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'Evolutionary Anachronisms\n\nEarth''s ecosystems have been shaped by the rise and fall of large animals. Mammoths, mastodons, and other megafauna once played vital roles in dispersing seeds and shaping vegetation. Many were driven to extinction by a combination of climate change and human hunting. One tree species evolved large, tough fruits and sharp thorns, likely to attract large herbivores that could swallow the fruit whole and to deter smaller ones. Today, few animals find the fruit palatable, and the thorns serve little purpose. __BLANK__: the cause of megafauna extinction was not climate or hunting alone but a complex interplay of factors, and the tree''s traits are remnants of a lost world.\n\nThe tree''s range contracted after the megafauna disappeared. How it survived at all is a puzzle. One hypothesis is that humans who valued its wood for tools or weapons inadvertently spread its seeds. __BLANK__: the same species that may have contributed to megafauna decline later became essential to the survival of a plant that had depended on those animals. Human agency, often destructive, sometimes filled an ecological gap.\n\nBiologists call such species evolutionary anachronisms. It is tempting to assume the tree has __BLANK__—that in the millennia since the megafauna vanished, it should have adapted to new dispersers or shed its now-useless traits. Yet the tree can live for centuries, and a few thousand years is a short time in evolutionary terms. New adaptations on that scale often require millions of years. The tree persists not because it has failed to evolve but because it has endured.',
  'Evolutionary Anachronisms',
  E'Evolutionary Anachronisms\n\nEarth''s ecosystems have been shaped by the rise and fall of large animals. Mammoths, mastodons, and other megafauna once played vital roles in dispersing seeds and shaping vegetation. Many were driven to extinction by a combination of climate change and human hunting. One tree species evolved large, tough fruits and sharp thorns, likely to attract large herbivores that could swallow the fruit whole and to deter smaller ones. Today, few animals find the fruit palatable, and the thorns serve little purpose. __BLANK__: the cause of megafauna extinction was not climate or hunting alone but a complex interplay of factors, and the tree''s traits are remnants of a lost world.\n\nThe tree''s range contracted after the megafauna disappeared. How it survived at all is a puzzle. One hypothesis is that humans who valued its wood for tools or weapons inadvertently spread its seeds. __BLANK__: the same species that may have contributed to megafauna decline later became essential to the survival of a plant that had depended on those animals. Human agency, often destructive, sometimes filled an ecological gap.\n\nBiologists call such species evolutionary anachronisms. It is tempting to assume the tree has __BLANK__—that in the millennia since the megafauna vanished, it should have adapted to new dispersers or shed its now-useless traits. Yet the tree can live for centuries, and a few thousand years is a short time in evolutionary terms. New adaptations on that scale often require millions of years. The tree persists not because it has failed to evolve but because it has endured.'
);
