-- ========== 7: The Origins of Writing ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'The Origins of Writing\n\nWriting systems emerged independently in several parts of the world: Mesopotamia, Egypt, China, and Mesoamerica. The earliest forms were often tied to accounting and administration rather than literature. Clay tablets from ancient Mesopotamia record quantities of grain, livestock, and labor. __BLANK__: writing was not initially a means of self-expression but a tool for managing complex economies and bureaucracies. Only later did it come to record myths, laws, and chronicles.\n\nScholars once assumed that writing spread from a single source. __BLANK__. The structures of Chinese characters, Egyptian hieroglyphs, and Mayan glyphs are too different to have sprung from one origin. Each system reflects the language and needs of the society that developed it. The invention of writing was a cognitive and social breakthrough that occurred multiple times in human history.\n\n__BLANK__. Societies with writing could preserve knowledge across generations, coordinate large populations, and develop more elaborate legal and religious traditions. The transition from oral to written culture did not simply add a new technology; it altered how people thought about memory, authority, and the past. The consequences of that transition are still with us today.',
  'The Origins of Writing',
  E'The Origins of Writing\n\nWriting systems emerged independently in several parts of the world: Mesopotamia, Egypt, China, and Mesoamerica. The earliest forms were often tied to accounting and administration rather than literature. Clay tablets from ancient Mesopotamia record quantities of grain, livestock, and labor. __BLANK__: writing was not initially a means of self-expression but a tool for managing complex economies and bureaucracies. Only later did it come to record myths, laws, and chronicles.\n\nScholars once assumed that writing spread from a single source. __BLANK__. The structures of Chinese characters, Egyptian hieroglyphs, and Mayan glyphs are too different to have sprung from one origin. Each system reflects the language and needs of the society that developed it. The invention of writing was a cognitive and social breakthrough that occurred multiple times in human history.\n\n__BLANK__. Societies with writing could preserve knowledge across generations, coordinate large populations, and develop more elaborate legal and religious traditions. The transition from oral to written culture did not simply add a new technology; it altered how people thought about memory, authority, and the past. The consequences of that transition are still with us today.'
);
