-- ========== 8: Climate and Civilization ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'Climate and Civilization\n\nHistorians have long debated the role of climate in the collapse of ancient societies. Drought, crop failure, and resource scarcity are often cited as factors in the decline of once-powerful states. __BLANK__: climate alone rarely explains collapse. Political instability, conflict, overexpansion, and social inequality typically interacted with environmental stress. A society that had depleted its soils or overexploited its forests was more vulnerable when drought or cooling arrived.\n\nPaleoclimatologists use ice cores, tree rings, and sediment layers to reconstruct past climates. These records show that some periods of upheaval coincided with sharp shifts in temperature or rainfall. __BLANK__: did climate change cause the collapse, or did it merely accelerate processes already underway? In many cases, the answer is both. Environmental change exposed weaknesses that might otherwise have been managed or postponed.\n\n__BLANK__. Today we face not only natural variability but human-induced warming, and the same questions apply: how resilient are our institutions, and how quickly can we adapt? The lessons of the past do not offer simple parallels, but they remind us that civilizations have always existed in dialogue with the climate, and that the margin between stability and crisis can be narrow.',
  'Climate and Civilization',
  E'Climate and Civilization\n\nHistorians have long debated the role of climate in the collapse of ancient societies. Drought, crop failure, and resource scarcity are often cited as factors in the decline of once-powerful states. __BLANK__: climate alone rarely explains collapse. Political instability, conflict, overexpansion, and social inequality typically interacted with environmental stress. A society that had depleted its soils or overexploited its forests was more vulnerable when drought or cooling arrived.\n\nPaleoclimatologists use ice cores, tree rings, and sediment layers to reconstruct past climates. These records show that some periods of upheaval coincided with sharp shifts in temperature or rainfall. __BLANK__: did climate change cause the collapse, or did it merely accelerate processes already underway? In many cases, the answer is both. Environmental change exposed weaknesses that might otherwise have been managed or postponed.\n\n__BLANK__. Today we face not only natural variability but human-induced warming, and the same questions apply: how resilient are our institutions, and how quickly can we adapt? The lessons of the past do not offer simple parallels, but they remind us that civilizations have always existed in dialogue with the climate, and that the margin between stability and crisis can be narrow.'
);
