-- ========== 9: The Placebo Effect ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'The Placebo Effect\n\nWhen patients in clinical trials receive an inactive substance—a sugar pill or saline injection—they sometimes improve anyway. This phenomenon is known as the placebo effect. For decades it was dismissed as "all in the mind" or as a nuisance that had to be controlled for in drug trials. __BLANK__: the placebo effect is a real physiological response. Brain imaging has shown that placebos can trigger the release of endorphins and activate regions involved in pain relief and expectation. The mind can influence the body in measurable ways.\n\nThe strength of the effect varies. It tends to be larger when the treatment involves a ritual—injections often produce a stronger placebo response than pills—and when the patient trusts the clinician. __BLANK__: the context of care, not just the chemical content of a drug, shapes outcomes. This has ethical implications. Should doctors harness placebos deliberately? Most agree that deception is wrong, but some argue that open-label placebos—where patients are told they are receiving an inactive treatment—can still reduce symptoms in certain conditions.\n\n__BLANK__. Understanding how expectation and context affect health could lead to better trial design, more honest communication with patients, and perhaps ways to enhance the benefits of genuine treatments by optimizing the circumstances in which they are given.',
  'The Placebo Effect',
  E'The Placebo Effect\n\nWhen patients in clinical trials receive an inactive substance—a sugar pill or saline injection—they sometimes improve anyway. This phenomenon is known as the placebo effect. For decades it was dismissed as "all in the mind" or as a nuisance that had to be controlled for in drug trials. __BLANK__: the placebo effect is a real physiological response. Brain imaging has shown that placebos can trigger the release of endorphins and activate regions involved in pain relief and expectation. The mind can influence the body in measurable ways.\n\nThe strength of the effect varies. It tends to be larger when the treatment involves a ritual—injections often produce a stronger placebo response than pills—and when the patient trusts the clinician. __BLANK__: the context of care, not just the chemical content of a drug, shapes outcomes. This has ethical implications. Should doctors harness placebos deliberately? Most agree that deception is wrong, but some argue that open-label placebos—where patients are told they are receiving an inactive treatment—can still reduce symptoms in certain conditions.\n\n__BLANK__. Understanding how expectation and context affect health could lead to better trial design, more honest communication with patients, and perhaps ways to enhance the benefits of genuine treatments by optimizing the circumstances in which they are given.'
);
