-- ========== 11: Democracy and Dissent ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'Democracy and Dissent\n\nDemocratic theory holds that citizens should be able to criticize their government without fear of reprisal. Freedom of speech and assembly are not merely individual rights but prerequisites for collective decision-making. __BLANK__: a democracy that cannot tolerate dissent risks becoming an echo chamber, where flawed policies go unchallenged and minority views are silenced. History is replete with examples of governments that claimed to speak for the people while suppressing those who disagreed.\n\nYet all democracies place some limits on expression. Defamation, incitement to violence, and the spread of harmful falsehoods are often restricted. __BLANK__: where should the line be drawn between protected speech and speech that undermines the very conditions necessary for democratic debate? Different societies answer this question differently, and the answer can shift in times of crisis or polarization.\n\n__BLANK__. When trust in institutions erodes, people may turn to alternative sources of information, some of which spread conspiracy theories or demonize opponents. A healthy democracy depends not only on legal protections for speech but on a culture that values evidence, tolerates disagreement, and distinguishes between criticism and disinformation. Without that culture, the right to dissent can be weaponized against democracy itself.',
  'Democracy and Dissent',
  E'Democracy and Dissent\n\nDemocratic theory holds that citizens should be able to criticize their government without fear of reprisal. Freedom of speech and assembly are not merely individual rights but prerequisites for collective decision-making. __BLANK__: a democracy that cannot tolerate dissent risks becoming an echo chamber, where flawed policies go unchallenged and minority views are silenced. History is replete with examples of governments that claimed to speak for the people while suppressing those who disagreed.\n\nYet all democracies place some limits on expression. Defamation, incitement to violence, and the spread of harmful falsehoods are often restricted. __BLANK__: where should the line be drawn between protected speech and speech that undermines the very conditions necessary for democratic debate? Different societies answer this question differently, and the answer can shift in times of crisis or polarization.\n\n__BLANK__. When trust in institutions erodes, people may turn to alternative sources of information, some of which spread conspiracy theories or demonize opponents. A healthy democracy depends not only on legal protections for speech but on a culture that values evidence, tolerates disagreement, and distinguishes between criticism and disinformation. Without that culture, the right to dissent can be weaponized against democracy itself.'
);
