-- ========== 12: Language and Thought ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'Language and Thought\n\nThe question of whether language shapes thought has fascinated philosophers and linguists for centuries. Some argued that we can only think what we can say—that language is the medium of thought. Others insisted that thought is independent of language and that we often struggle to put our ideas into words. __BLANK__: speakers of languages that lack distinct words for certain colors can still perceive color differences, but they may categorize and remember colors differently from speakers of languages with richer color vocabularies. Language does not determine perception, but it can influence how we attend to and encode experience.\n\nResearchers have studied speakers of languages that use cardinal directions (north, south) instead of relative terms (left, right) for spatial description. Such speakers maintain a constant sense of orientation and perform better on some spatial tasks. __BLANK__: the structure of a language can encourage habits of attention and cognition that persist even when one is not speaking. This does not mean that thought is a prisoner of language, but that language is one of the tools with which we construct our mental world.\n\n__BLANK__. Bilinguals sometimes report that they feel like different people in different languages, or that certain emotions are easier to express in one language than another. Such reports are subjective, but they hint at the ways in which language is bound up with identity, memory, and emotion—not just with cold cognition.',
  'Language and Thought',
  E'Language and Thought\n\nThe question of whether language shapes thought has fascinated philosophers and linguists for centuries. Some argued that we can only think what we can say—that language is the medium of thought. Others insisted that thought is independent of language and that we often struggle to put our ideas into words. __BLANK__: speakers of languages that lack distinct words for certain colors can still perceive color differences, but they may categorize and remember colors differently from speakers of languages with richer color vocabularies. Language does not determine perception, but it can influence how we attend to and encode experience.\n\nResearchers have studied speakers of languages that use cardinal directions (north, south) instead of relative terms (left, right) for spatial description. Such speakers maintain a constant sense of orientation and perform better on some spatial tasks. __BLANK__: the structure of a language can encourage habits of attention and cognition that persist even when one is not speaking. This does not mean that thought is a prisoner of language, but that language is one of the tools with which we construct our mental world.\n\n__BLANK__. Bilinguals sometimes report that they feel like different people in different languages, or that certain emotions are easier to express in one language than another. Such reports are subjective, but they hint at the ways in which language is bound up with identity, memory, and emotion—not just with cold cognition.'
);
