-- ========== 13: The Cost of Economic Growth ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'The Cost of Economic Growth\n\nFor much of the twentieth century, economic growth was seen as an unqualified good. Rising GDP meant more jobs, higher incomes, and better living standards. Since the 1970s, however, economists and environmentalists have questioned whether growth can continue indefinitely on a finite planet. __BLANK__: the depletion of natural resources, pollution, and climate change are often treated as "externalities" in conventional economics—costs not reflected in market prices. As a result, growth can be overstated and its true cost underestimated.\n\nSome have called for "degrowth" or a shift to well-being indicators that go beyond GDP. Others argue that innovation and green technology can decouple growth from environmental damage. __BLANK__: the evidence is mixed. Some countries have reduced carbon emissions while growing their economies, but global material use and emissions have continued to rise. Efficiency gains have often been offset by increased consumption.\n\n__BLANK__. The question is not only whether growth is sustainable but who benefits from it and who bears its costs. Inequality within and between nations has grown in many places, and the benefits of growth have not always reached the poorest. A rethinking of progress may require not only new metrics but new policies that distribute the gains—and share the burdens—more fairly.',
  'The Cost of Economic Growth',
  E'The Cost of Economic Growth\n\nFor much of the twentieth century, economic growth was seen as an unqualified good. Rising GDP meant more jobs, higher incomes, and better living standards. Since the 1970s, however, economists and environmentalists have questioned whether growth can continue indefinitely on a finite planet. __BLANK__: the depletion of natural resources, pollution, and climate change are often treated as "externalities" in conventional economics—costs not reflected in market prices. As a result, growth can be overstated and its true cost underestimated.\n\nSome have called for "degrowth" or a shift to well-being indicators that go beyond GDP. Others argue that innovation and green technology can decouple growth from environmental damage. __BLANK__: the evidence is mixed. Some countries have reduced carbon emissions while growing their economies, but global material use and emissions have continued to rise. Efficiency gains have often been offset by increased consumption.\n\n__BLANK__. The question is not only whether growth is sustainable but who benefits from it and who bears its costs. Inequality within and between nations has grown in many places, and the benefits of growth have not always reached the poorest. A rethinking of progress may require not only new metrics but new policies that distribute the gains—and share the burdens—more fairly.'
);
