-- ========== 14: The Evolution of Cooperation ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'The Evolution of Cooperation\n\nWhy do humans cooperate with strangers, sometimes at great cost to themselves? Evolutionary theory has long emphasized competition and survival of the fittest. Yet cooperation is widespread in nature and in human societies. __BLANK__: under the right conditions, cooperative behavior can be favored by natural selection. If individuals interact repeatedly and can recognize one another, strategies that reward cooperation and punish defection can thrive. Tit-for-tat and similar rules can emerge and persist.\n\nHuman cooperation extends beyond kin and small groups. We pay taxes, follow rules, and contribute to public goods even when we could free-ride. __BLANK__: norms, reputation, and institutions allow cooperation to scale. Societies that develop ways to enforce norms and punish cheaters can sustain larger and more complex forms of collective action. Culture and institutions thus become part of the story of how cooperation evolved.\n\n__BLANK__. Climate change, pandemics, and nuclear proliferation require coordination at a global scale. The same mechanisms that enabled cooperation within groups—reciprocity, reputation, punishment—may be insufficient when the group is all of humanity and the stakes are existential. Understanding the evolution of cooperation may be essential to designing institutions that can meet twenty-first-century challenges.',
  'The Evolution of Cooperation',
  E'The Evolution of Cooperation\n\nWhy do humans cooperate with strangers, sometimes at great cost to themselves? Evolutionary theory has long emphasized competition and survival of the fittest. Yet cooperation is widespread in nature and in human societies. __BLANK__: under the right conditions, cooperative behavior can be favored by natural selection. If individuals interact repeatedly and can recognize one another, strategies that reward cooperation and punish defection can thrive. Tit-for-tat and similar rules can emerge and persist.\n\nHuman cooperation extends beyond kin and small groups. We pay taxes, follow rules, and contribute to public goods even when we could free-ride. __BLANK__: norms, reputation, and institutions allow cooperation to scale. Societies that develop ways to enforce norms and punish cheaters can sustain larger and more complex forms of collective action. Culture and institutions thus become part of the story of how cooperation evolved.\n\n__BLANK__. Climate change, pandemics, and nuclear proliferation require coordination at a global scale. The same mechanisms that enabled cooperation within groups—reciprocity, reputation, punishment—may be insufficient when the group is all of humanity and the stakes are existential. Understanding the evolution of cooperation may be essential to designing institutions that can meet twenty-first-century challenges.'
);
