-- ========== 15: The Rise of Cities ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'The Rise of Cities\n\nFor most of human history, the majority of people lived in rural areas. The shift to an urban majority is recent and accelerating. Cities concentrate people, capital, and innovation; they generate a disproportionate share of economic output and cultural production. __BLANK__: cities also concentrate poverty, pollution, and vulnerability to disease. The same density that enables creativity and exchange can also amplify inequality and risk. Urbanization is not uniformly beneficial.\n\nHistorians trace the first cities to the emergence of agriculture and surplus production. Once some people could be freed from farming, they could specialize in crafts, trade, administration, or religion. __BLANK__: cities have always been nodes of power, but also of diversity and dissent. They attract migrants, mix cultures, and sometimes challenge the authority of rulers. The city has been both the seat of empire and the cradle of revolution.\n\n__BLANK__. Climate change will test urban infrastructure: heat waves, floods, and rising seas threaten coastal megacities. Pandemics spread quickly in dense populations. The future of humanity is urban, and the quality of that future will depend on how we design cities—for resilience, equity, and sustainability—in the decades to come.',
  'The Rise of Cities',
  E'The Rise of Cities\n\nFor most of human history, the majority of people lived in rural areas. The shift to an urban majority is recent and accelerating. Cities concentrate people, capital, and innovation; they generate a disproportionate share of economic output and cultural production. __BLANK__: cities also concentrate poverty, pollution, and vulnerability to disease. The same density that enables creativity and exchange can also amplify inequality and risk. Urbanization is not uniformly beneficial.\n\nHistorians trace the first cities to the emergence of agriculture and surplus production. Once some people could be freed from farming, they could specialize in crafts, trade, administration, or religion. __BLANK__: cities have always been nodes of power, but also of diversity and dissent. They attract migrants, mix cultures, and sometimes challenge the authority of rulers. The city has been both the seat of empire and the cradle of revolution.\n\n__BLANK__. Climate change will test urban infrastructure: heat waves, floods, and rising seas threaten coastal megacities. Pandemics spread quickly in dense populations. The future of humanity is urban, and the quality of that future will depend on how we design cities—for resilience, equity, and sustainability—in the decades to come.'
);
