-- ========== 16: Art and Censorship ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'Art and Censorship\n\nGovernments and institutions have long sought to control what art is made, displayed, or performed. The reasons given are often moral or political: to protect the public from offensive content, to uphold religious or ideological orthodoxy, or to maintain social order. __BLANK__: censorship can also suppress dissent, silence minority voices, and stifle the experimentation that has produced many of the works we now consider masterpieces. The same power that can shield audiences can be used to enforce conformity.\n\nArtists have responded in various ways. Some have complied, some have gone into exile, and some have found ways to encode subversive messages in allegory or abstraction. __BLANK__: what one era condemns as obscene or blasphemous, another may celebrate as bold or prophetic. The history of art is in part a history of boundaries being tested and redrawn. Today''s controversies over representation, appropriation, and offense echo earlier debates, even if the terms have changed.\n\n__BLANK__. In liberal democracies, legal protections for artistic expression are strong but not absolute; obscenity, incitement, and in some places hate speech may be restricted. The harder questions often concern not the law but social pressure: when does criticism become censorship, and when does the artist''s freedom conflict with the dignity or safety of others? There are no easy answers, but the conversation itself is a sign of a society that takes both art and accountability seriously.',
  'Art and Censorship',
  E'Art and Censorship\n\nGovernments and institutions have long sought to control what art is made, displayed, or performed. The reasons given are often moral or political: to protect the public from offensive content, to uphold religious or ideological orthodoxy, or to maintain social order. __BLANK__: censorship can also suppress dissent, silence minority voices, and stifle the experimentation that has produced many of the works we now consider masterpieces. The same power that can shield audiences can be used to enforce conformity.\n\nArtists have responded in various ways. Some have complied, some have gone into exile, and some have found ways to encode subversive messages in allegory or abstraction. __BLANK__: what one era condemns as obscene or blasphemous, another may celebrate as bold or prophetic. The history of art is in part a history of boundaries being tested and redrawn. Today''s controversies over representation, appropriation, and offense echo earlier debates, even if the terms have changed.\n\n__BLANK__. In liberal democracies, legal protections for artistic expression are strong but not absolute; obscenity, incitement, and in some places hate speech may be restricted. The harder questions often concern not the law but social pressure: when does criticism become censorship, and when does the artist''s freedom conflict with the dignity or safety of others? There are no easy answers, but the conversation itself is a sign of a society that takes both art and accountability seriously.'
);
