-- ========== 17: The Limits of Memory ==========
INSERT INTO public.reading_passages (level, genre, passage_type, body, title, content)
VALUES (
  '1級', 'expository', 'long_fill',
  E'The Limits of Memory\n\nMemory is not a perfect recording of the past. Decades of research have shown that we reconstruct rather than replay our experiences. Each time we recall an event, we may subtly alter it; over time, memories can drift, merge, or be contaminated by suggestion. __BLANK__: eyewitness testimony, once considered among the most reliable forms of evidence, is now treated with caution in courts. Innocent people have been convicted on the basis of confident but false memories.\n\nYet memory is also adaptive. We do not need to store every detail of every moment; we extract gist, meaning, and lessons. Forgetting can be functional—it clears space and allows us to generalize. __BLANK__: the same flexibility that allows us to learn and adapt also makes us vulnerable to distortion. The line between healthy reconstruction and harmful false memory is not always clear, especially in cases of trauma or when memories are recovered after long periods.\n\n__BLANK__. Technologies that could enhance or implant memories raise ethical questions: who should have access, and for what purposes? The prospect of editing or erasing memories—once the stuff of science fiction—is now a subject of serious research. As the science advances, society will need to decide how much we value memory as a record of the past versus as a resource we might one day be able to modify.',
  'The Limits of Memory',
  E'The Limits of Memory\n\nMemory is not a perfect recording of the past. Decades of research have shown that we reconstruct rather than replay our experiences. Each time we recall an event, we may subtly alter it; over time, memories can drift, merge, or be contaminated by suggestion. __BLANK__: eyewitness testimony, once considered among the most reliable forms of evidence, is now treated with caution in courts. Innocent people have been convicted on the basis of confident but false memories.\n\nYet memory is also adaptive. We do not need to store every detail of every moment; we extract gist, meaning, and lessons. Forgetting can be functional—it clears space and allows us to generalize. __BLANK__: the same flexibility that allows us to learn and adapt also makes us vulnerable to distortion. The line between healthy reconstruction and harmful false memory is not always clear, especially in cases of trauma or when memories are recovered after long periods.\n\n__BLANK__. Technologies that could enhance or implant memories raise ethical questions: who should have access, and for what purposes? The prospect of editing or erasing memories—once the stuff of science fiction—is now a subject of serious research. As the science advances, society will need to decide how much we value memory as a record of the past versus as a resource we might one day be able to modify.'
